                </div>
                <div class="summary-item">
                    <div class="summary-item-label">Annual Net Pay</div>
                    <div class="summary-item-value" id="sum-net" style="color: var(--color-takehome);">$0</div>
                </div>
                <div class="summary-item">
                    <div class="summary-item-label">Monthly Net Pay</div>
                    <div class="summary-item-value" id="sum-monthly" style="color: var(--color-takehome);">$0</div>
                </div>
                <div class="summary-item">
                    <div class="summary-item-label">Effective Rate</div>
                    <div class="summary-item-value" id="sum-rate">0%</div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- State Tax Comparison -->
        <div class="section-card">
            <h2>State Income Tax Comparison</h2>
            <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Based on your current gross salary. Shows estimated state tax and take-home pay by state.</p>
            <div class="two-col-tables">
                <div>
                    <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-takehome);">Top 10 Lowest Tax States</h3>
                    <div class="state-table-wrap">
                        <table class="state-table" id="low-tax-table">
                            <thead>
                                <tr>
                                    <th>State</th>
                                    <th>Rate</th>
                                    <th>Annual Tax</th>
                                    <th>Take Home</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody id="low-tax-tbody"></tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-medicare);">Top 10 Highest Tax States</h3>
                    <div class="state-table-wrap">
                        <table class="state-table" id="high-tax-table">
                            <thead>
                                <tr>
                                    <th>State</th>
                                    <th>Rate</th>
                                    <th>Annual Tax</th>
                                    <th>Take Home</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody id="high-tax-tbody"></tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Use This Paycheck Calculator</h2>
            <p>Enter your gross salary (annual or per-paycheck amount), select your pay frequency, filing status, and state. Optionally add your 401(k) contribution percentage and health insurance premium per paycheck. The calculator instantly estimates your federal income tax, state income tax, Social Security, Medicare, and net take-home pay for each paycheck and annually.</p>
            <p>Use the per-paycheck and annual toggle to see your complete breakdown. The pie chart visualizes exactly where every dollar of your gross pay goes, making it easy to understand your total tax burden at a glance.</p>

            <h2>Understanding Your Salary After Taxes</h2>
            <p>Your take-home pay is determined by several mandatory deductions from your gross salary. Federal income tax uses progressive brackets — you pay increasing rates as your income rises through each bracket, not a flat rate on all income. The 2024 brackets range from 10% on the first $11,600 (single) to 37% on income over $609,350.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Federal Income Tax:</strong> Progressive tax based on filing status and taxable income after the standard deduction.</li>
                <li><strong>State Income Tax:</strong> Varies widely — nine states charge 0% while California's top rate reaches 13.3%.</li>
                <li><strong>Social Security (OASDI):</strong> 6.2% of gross wages up to $168,600 (2024 wage base).</li>
                <li><strong>Medicare:</strong> 1.45% on all wages, plus 0.9% surtax on wages over $200,000 (single).</li>
                <li><strong>Pre-tax Deductions:</strong> 401(k) contributions and health insurance reduce your taxable income for income tax purposes.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>How Pay Frequency Affects Your Paycheck</h2>
            <p>While pay frequency does not change your total annual tax burden, it affects the size of each individual paycheck. Biweekly pay (26 paychecks per year) is the most common in the US. Weekly pay results in smaller but more frequent checks. Monthly pay means fewer, larger checks. Semi-monthly pay (24 paychecks, typically on the 1st and 15th) is common for salaried employees. The calculator adjusts all deductions proportionally for your selected pay frequency.</p>

            <h2>Maximizing Your Take-Home Pay</h2>
            <p>Several strategies can legally increase your net pay. Adjusting your W-4 withholding to match your actual tax liability prevents over-withholding (and eliminates those large refunds that are really interest-free loans to the government). Pre-tax contributions to 401(k), HSA, and FSA accounts reduce your taxable income. If you have flexibility in where you live, relocating to a state with no income tax — like Texas, Florida, or Washington — can save thousands per year. Use the state comparison table below the calculator to see exactly how much you would save.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            {faqSchema.mainEntity.map((item) => (
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <div class="faq-question">{item.name}</div>
                    <div class="faq-answer">{item.acceptedAnswer.text}</div>
                </div>
            ))}
